'''Rush''' is a [[Canadian rock|Canadian]] [[Rock music|rock]] [[rock band|band]] comprising [[bass guitar|bassist]], [[keyboard instrument|keyboardist]], and [[singer|lead vocalist]] [[Geddy Lee]], [[electric guitar|guitar]]ist [[Alex Lifeson]], and [[drum kit|drummer]] and [[lyricist]] [[Neil Peart]]. Rush was formed in the summer of 1968, in the neighbourhood of [[Willowdale, Toronto|Willowdale]] in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], by Alex Lifeson, [[Jeff_Jones_(musician)|Jeff Jones]], and [[John Rutsey]]. Geddy Lee replaced Jeff Jones in September 1968. After various ephemeral lineup fluctuations, Neil Peart replaced Rutsey on drums in July 1974, two weeks before the group's first U.S. tour, to complete the present line-up. Since the release of the band's [[Rush (album)|self-titled debut album]] in 1974 Rush  has become known for the instrumental virtuosity of its members, complex compositions, and eclectic lyrical motifs drawing heavily on [[science fiction]], [[fantasy]], [[libertarian]] [[philosophy]], as well as addressing humanitarian, social, emotional, and environmental concerns. 

Musically, Rush's style has evolved over the years, beginning in the vein of blues-inspired [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] on their eponymous debut to styles encompassing [[hard rock]], [[progressive rock]], a period dominated by [[synthesizers]] and, more recently, [[modern rock]]. Rush has influenced various modern artists such as [[Metallica]],<ref name = "Austin Chronicle">Austin Chronicle Music [http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Issue/review?oid=oid%3A218424 Rush's 30th Anniversary Tour], Accessed [[16 August]] [[2006]]</ref><ref>[http://egodeath.com/MysticStateAllusionsMetallicaLyrics.htm Metallica thanks Rush] Accessed [[August 15]] [[2007]]</ref> [[The Smashing Pumpkins]]<ref name = "CNN">CNN.com [http://www.cnn.com/interactive/entertainment/0205/rush.thru.decades/content.3.html Rush profile] Accessed [[17 August]] [[2006]]</ref> and [[Primus (band)|Primus]],<ref name = "CNN"/> as well as many notable [[progressive metal]] bands such as [[Dream Theater]]<ref name = "Austin Chronicle"/> and [[Symphony X]].<ref name = "Symphony X">Symphony X Official website [http://www.symphonyx.com/faq_band.html FAQ] Accessed [[16 August]] [[2006]]</ref> 

Rush has been awarded several [[Juno Awards]]<ref>Juno Awards [http://www.junoawards.ca/archive_past.php Juno Archives] Accessed [[16 March]] [[2006]]</ref> and was inducted into the [[Canadian Music Hall of Fame]] in 1994.<ref>[http://www.junoawards.ca/halloffame_past.php Canadian Music Hall of Fame] Accessed [[16 March]] [[2006]]</ref> Over the course of their career, the individual members of Rush have been recognized as some of the most proficient players on their respective instruments with each member winning several awards in magazine readers' polls.<ref>[http://www.geocities.com/SunsetStrip/Amphitheatre/2740/rmem.html Individual awards list Accessed [[16 July]] [[2007]]</ref> As a whole, Rush boasts 23 [[music recording sales certification|gold records]] and 14 platinum (3 multi-platinum) records. These statistics place Rush fifth behind [[The Beatles]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] and [[Aerosmith]] for the most consecutive gold and platinum albums by a rock band.<ref>RIAA Top Artists [http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=tblTopArt] Recording Industry Association of America Accessed [[July 29th]], [[2007]] </ref> Rush ranks 76th in U.S. album sales according to the RIAA with sales of 25 million units.<ref>RIAA Top Artists [http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=tblTopArt] Recording Industry Association of America Accessed [[July 29th]], [[2007]]
</ref> Although total worldwide album sales are not calculated by any single entity, as of 2004 several industry sources estimated Rush's total worldwide album sales at over 40 million units.<ref>[http://classicrock.about.com/od/bandsandartists/p/rush_profile.htm] Classicrock.about.com by Dave White </ref><ref>[http://www.freerepublic.com/focus/news/675572/posts] Freerepublic.com April 30th, 2002</ref><ref>[http://www.rockreport.be/news.asp?monthyear=102005&start=20 Rockreport, Claim for 40 million sold albums, Oktober 5th, 2005]</ref><ref>{{cite news 
